solutions.content:
**EDIT: Original post title:** *Leetcode hint misleading? Is there any C++ solution with Trie and set of ptrs that does not TLE?*

Leetcode hint says : *Put the words into a trie, and manage a set of pointers within that trie.*

ok Leetcode, I did that but this TLE because of the dumb test case 17.

On the discussion, the non TLE C++ solutions I have seen are:
- trie of reversed words + complete lookup on the word formed by the the stream of chars (capped by max(words size)), not very elegant, this suffer from compete word lookup at each character
- Aho - Corasick algorithm, quite complex and with ridiculously long and complex implementations

So my question is : **Is there a solution that uses trie AND manage a set of pointers in the trie that DOES NOT TLE ???**

**EDIT: Here is the list of solutions I tried (and the answer to my question seems to be NO)** 

1 - trie (using unique_ptr for nodes) of words + deque of pointers -> TLE on test 16
2 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) + vector of pointers & additional tmp vector of pointers -> TLE on test  16
3 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) + circular queue (ring buffer) of pointers -> TLE on test 16 or 17
4 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes, preallocated in a vector of Trie) + circular queue (ring buffer) of pointers -> TLE on test 17 or all tests pass but TLE on overall execution
5 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) of reversed words + deque<char> as stream buffer -> Accepted ~900ms
6 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes, preallocated in a vector of Trie) of reversed words + deque as stream buffer  -> Accepted 496 ms, 80.56% best try

**Conclusion:**  
This problem is rubbish, I will downvote it.
The leetcode hint is always TLE.
The solution that uses reversed words is idiotic since it only improves the situations for special cases like:
- `word = "aaaa...repeat until bored...aaaab"`
- `strm = "aaaa...repeat until bored...aaaac"`

But reversed word approach would **TLE miserably as well** for test case such as:
- `word = "aaaa...repeat like hell...aaaa"`
- `strm = "aaaa...repeat like hell...aaa"`

**-> Thank you leetcode** for the **low quality of your test cases** that lead to produce bad solution that work ok for specific corner cases!!

**Detailled code of all studied solutions:**

**1 - trie (using unique_ptr for nodes) of words + deque of pointers -> TLE on test 16**

This is my original solution:
- just implement a Trie made of an array of `unique_ptr<Trie>`
- use a deque to manage pointer to Trie nodes
```
class StreamChecker {
    struct Trie{
        array<unique_ptr<Trie>, 26> letters;
        bool is_word;
        bool is_leaf;

        Trie():letters{}, is_word(false), is_leaf(true){}

        void insert(const string& word, int pos=0){
            if(pos == word.size()){
                is_word = true;
                return;
            }
            is_leaf = false;
            char c = word[pos];
            auto &ptr_ref = letters[c - 'a'];
            if(!ptr_ref)
                ptr_ref = make_unique<Trie>();
            ptr_ref->insert(word, pos+1);
        }

        Trie *find(char c){
            return letters[c-'a'].get();
        }
    };

    Trie trie_;
    deque<Trie *> nodes_;
public:
    StreamChecker(vector<string>& words) {
        for(const auto& w: words)
            trie_.insert(w);
        nodes_.emplace_back(&trie_);
    }

    bool query(char letter) {
        bool result = false;
        for(int i = 0, size = nodes_.size(); i != size; ++i){
            auto n = nodes_.front();
            nodes_.pop_front();
            if(auto node = n->find(letter); node != nullptr){
                result |= node->is_word;
                if(!node->is_leaf)
                    nodes_.emplace_back(node);
            }
        }
        nodes_.emplace_back(&trie_);
        return result;
    }
};
```
**2 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) + vector of pointers & additional tmp vector of pointers -> TLE on test  16**

Ok, here were my thoughts to improve the performances of 1:
- let's not use convenient unique_ptr and manage deallocation myself
- push and pop in deque result of popping a node when dequeing and possibly reinserting after (for the same char in the stream), so lets use more memory efficient container: vector<Trie*> + a temporary one
- reserve the size of temporary vector to minimize the cost of re-allocations (when the vector reaches its internal capacity)
- after building the temporary vector, move it to the main one

```
class StreamChecker {
    struct Trie{
        array<Trie *, 26> letters;
        bool is_word;
        bool is_leaf;

        Trie():letters{}, is_word(false), is_leaf(true){}
        ~Trie(){for(auto ptr: letters) if(ptr) delete ptr;}

        void insert(const string& word, int pos=0){
            if(pos == word.size()){
                is_word = true;
                return;
            }
            is_leaf = false;
            char c = word[pos];
            auto &ptr_ref = letters[c - 'a'];
            if(!ptr_ref) ptr_ref = new Trie();
            ptr_ref->insert(word, pos+1);
        }
    };

    Trie trie_;
    vector<Trie *> nodes_;
public:
    StreamChecker(vector<string>& words) {
        for(const auto& w: words)
            trie_.insert(w);
        nodes_.emplace_back(&trie_);
    }

    bool query(char letter) {
        bool result = false;
        vector<Trie *> new_nodes;
        new_nodes.reserve(nodes_.size()+1);
        for(int i = 0, size = nodes_.size(); i != size; ++i){
            auto n = nodes_[i];
            if(auto node = n->letters[letter-'a']; node != nullptr){
                result |= node->is_word;
                if(!node->is_leaf) new_nodes.emplace_back(node);
            }
        }
        new_nodes.emplace_back(&trie_);
        nodes_ = move(new_nodes);
        return result;
    }
};
```
**3 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) + circular queue (ring buffer) of pointers -> TLE on test 16 or 17**

I thought that both in 1 & 2, there are a lot of allocations / deallocations happening so:
- let's use a circular queue to kill any dynamic allocation when processing the stream
- intialise the circular queue to the maximum possible size (max words sizes +1))
```
template <typename T>
class MyCircularQueue {
    int k_;
    vector<T> buffer_;
    typename vector<T>::iterator front_;
    typename vector<T>::iterator back_;
    int size_;
public:
    MyCircularQueue(int k):
        k_(k),buffer_(k_), front_(buffer_.begin()), back_(buffer_.begin()),size_(0){}
    MyCircularQueue(){}

    void resize(int k){
        k_ = k;
        buffer_.resize(k_);
        front_ = buffer_.begin();
        back_ = buffer_.begin();
        size_= 0;
    }

    void push_back(T value) {
        back_ = (size_ && ++back_ == buffer_.end())?buffer_.begin():back_;
        *back_ = value;
        ++size_;
    }

    T pop_front() {
        auto tmp = *front_;
        front_ = (front_ != back_ && ++front_ == buffer_.end())?buffer_.begin():front_;
        --size_;
        return tmp;
    }

    T& front() {return *front_;}
    T& back() {return *back_;}
    int size() {return size_;}
};

class StreamChecker {
    struct Trie{
        array<Trie *, 26> letters;
        bool is_word;
        bool is_leaf;

        Trie():letters{}, is_word(false), is_leaf(true){}
        ~Trie(){for(auto ptr: letters) if(ptr) delete ptr;}

        void insert(const string& word, int pos=0){
            if(pos == word.size()){
                is_word = true;
                return;
            }
            is_leaf = false;
            char c = word[pos];
            auto &ptr_ref = letters[c - 'a'];
            if(!ptr_ref)
                ptr_ref = new Trie();
            ptr_ref->insert(word, pos+1);
        }
    };

    Trie trie_;
    MyCircularQueue<Trie *> queue_;
    size_t maxwordsize_;
public:
    StreamChecker(vector<string>& words):maxwordsize_(0) {
        for(const auto& w: words){
            trie_.insert(w);
            maxwordsize_ = max(maxwordsize_, w.size());
        }
        queue_.resize(maxwordsize_+1);
        queue_.push_back(&trie_);
    }

    bool query(char letter) {
        bool result = false;
        for(int i = 0, size=queue_.size(); i!= size; ++i){
            auto n = queue_.pop_front();
            if(auto node = n->letters[letter-'a']; node){
                result |= node->is_word;
                if(!node->is_leaf) queue_.push_back(node);
            }
        }
        queue_.push_back(&trie_);
        return result;
    }
};
```

**4 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes, preallocated in a vector of Trie) + circular queue (ring buffer) of pointers -> TLE on test 17 or all tests pass but TLE on overall execution**

Ok, I was already pretty pissed with that problem at that stage but I thought that the word sizes in test 16 & 17 were pretty long and then building the Trie woud lead to a good number of allocations for all the Trie nodes. so I did this:
- compute the maximum possible number of tries nodes : sum( words sizes +1 )
- create a vector of Tries `trie_nodes_pool_` and reserve the necessary space in memory
- replace `ptr = new Trie()` per 'trie_nodes_pool_.emplace(); ptr = &trie_nodes_pool_.back();`
```
template <typename T>
class MyCircularQueue {
    int k_;
    vector<T> buffer_;
    typename vector<T>::iterator front_;
    typename vector<T>::iterator back_;
    int size_;
public:
    MyCircularQueue(int k):
        k_(k),buffer_(k_), front_(buffer_.begin()), back_(buffer_.begin()),size_(0){}
    MyCircularQueue(){}

    void resize(int k){
        k_ = k;
        buffer_.resize(k_);
        front_ = buffer_.begin();
        back_ = buffer_.begin();
        size_= 0;
    }

    void push_back(T value) {
        back_ = (size_ && ++back_ == buffer_.end())?buffer_.begin():back_;
        *back_ = value;
        ++size_;
    }

    T pop_front() {
        auto tmp = *front_;
        front_ = (front_ != back_ && ++front_ == buffer_.end())?buffer_.begin():front_;
        --size_;
        return tmp;
    }

    T& front() {return *front_;}
    T& back() {return *back_;}
    int size() {return size_;}
};

class StreamChecker {
    struct Trie{
        array<Trie *, 26> letters;
        bool is_word;
        bool is_leaf;

        Trie():letters{}, is_word(false), is_leaf(true){}
        void insert(const string& word, vector<Trie>& pool, int pos=0){
            if(pos == word.size()){
                is_word = true;
                return;
            }
            is_leaf = false;
            char c = word[pos];
            auto &ptr_ref = letters[c - 'a'];
            if(!ptr_ref){
                pool.emplace_back();
                ptr_ref = &pool.back();
            }
            ptr_ref->insert(word, pool, pos+1);
        }
    };

    Trie trie_;
    vector<Trie> trie_nodes_pool_;
    MyCircularQueue<Trie *> queue_;
public:
    StreamChecker(vector<string>& words){
        size_t total_size = 1;
        size_t maxwordsize = 0;
        for(const auto& w: words){
            maxwordsize = max(maxwordsize, w.size());
            total_size += w.size()+1;
        }
        trie_nodes_pool_.reserve(total_size);
        for(const auto& w: words)
            trie_.insert(w, trie_nodes_pool_);
        queue_.resize(maxwordsize+1);
        queue_.push_back(&trie_);
    }

    bool query(char letter) {
        bool result = false;
        for(int i = 0, size=queue_.size(); i!= size; ++i){
            auto n = queue_.pop_front();
            if(auto node = n->letters[letter-'a']; node){
                result |= node->is_word;
                if(!node->is_leaf) queue_.push_back(node);
            }
        }
        queue_.push_back(&trie_);
        return result;
    }
};
```

**5 - trie (using raw ptr for nodes) of reversed words + deque as stream buffer -> Accepted ~900ms**

Ok, at this point I was really thinking this hint from leetcode just made me waste my time as well as the 
solution using trie of reversed word was rubbish, but still I wanted to implelented it...
```
class StreamChecker {
    struct Trie{
        array<Trie *, 26> letters;
        bool is_word;
        bool is_leaf;

        Trie():letters{}, is_word(false), is_leaf(true){}
        ~Trie(){for(auto n: letters) if(n) delete(n);}

        void insert(const string& word, int pos=0){
            if(pos == word.size()){
                is_word = true;
                return;
            }
            is_leaf = false;
            char c = word[pos];
            auto &ptr_ref = letters[c - 'a'];
            if(!ptr_ref) ptr_ref = new Trie();
            ptr_ref->insert(word, pos+1);
        }

        template<typename Iterator>
        bool lookup(Iterator it, Iterator end){
            if(is_word || it == end) return is_word;
            if(auto node = letters[*it-'a']; node)
                return node->lookup(++it, end);
            return false;
        }
    };

    Trie trie_;
    deque<char> stream_buf_;
    size_t maxwordsize_ = 0;
public:
    StreamChecker(vector<string>& words):maxwordsize_(0){
        for(auto& w: words){
            maxwordsize_ = max(maxwordsize_, w.size());
            reverse(w.begin(), w.end());
            trie_.insert(w);
        }
    }

    bool query(char letter) {
        stream_buf_.push_front(letter);
        if(stream_buf_.size() > maxwordsize_)
            stream_buf_.pop_back();
        return trie_.lookup(stream_buf_.cbegin(), stream_buf_.cend());
    }
};
```

