This approach doesn't keep a list of input stream, but instead keep a list of promosing suffixes which is updated with each new letter.
Time complexity of `query` is O(min(M, N)), where M is the number of letters seen, and N is the number of nodes in trie.  
Based on online judge, this solution is generally slower but consumes much less space.  I think this approach is still better than solution article because it doesn't waste space to store input stream and in reality the number of promising suffixes at any time should be a small number compared to the size of input stream. (can't approve but just an intuition)

```python
class StreamChecker:
    def __init__(self, words: List[str]):
        self.WORD = '#'
        # build a trie of input words
        self.trie = {} # nested hashmap (dictionary)
        for word in words:
            node = self.trie
            for c in word:
                node = node.setdefault(c, {})
            node[self.WORD] = {}
         # list of trie nodes to store all promising suffixes seen so far
        self.suffixes = [self.trie]

    # Time: O(min(N, M)), N: number of letters seen, M: number of nodes in trie
    def query(self, letter: str) -> bool:
        new_suffixes = [self.trie]
        for suffix in self.suffixes:
            if letter in suffix:
                new_suffixes.append(suffix[letter])
        self.suffixes = new_suffixes
        for suffix in self.suffixes:
            if self.WORD in suffix:
                return True
        return False


# Your StreamChecker object will be instantiated and called as such:
# obj = StreamChecker(words)
# param_1 = obj.query(letter)
