solutions.content:
The gist of this solution is to calculate the rolling hash of each word, and map that hash value to the set of words which share that hash value (for a good hash function, different words having the same hash shouldn't happen often). In addition to this, we'll calculate the rolling hash for *all* of the suffixes in the word (e.g. for `"abc"` we would calculate/store the hashes for `"abc"`, `"bc"`, and `"c"`. If we move from the end of the stream backwards, this will allow us to quickly check whether or not each given suffix might actually exist, and if not, prevent unnecessarily checking other "substrings" in the stream which can not possibly be contained in our set of valid words.

After this initialization, whenever we call query, we will add the new character to the end of the character list, then work backwards to calculate a rolling hash while at the same time incrementally building a string. If we find a hash value that exists in our `wordHash` map, we can then check if the currently-constructed string exists in the set of words mapped to by that hash value, and if so, return true. If we reach the first character in the stream (or exceed the length of the longest word in our set) we return false. 

Here is my code:

```
class StreamChecker {
    static final int MOD = 100000007;
    int maxLen;
    Set<Integer> suffixes;
    Map<Integer, Set<String>> wordMap;
    List<Character> stream;
    public StreamChecker(String[] words) {
        maxLen = 0;
        suffixes = new HashSet<>();
        wordMap = new HashMap<>();
        for(String w : words) {
            addRollingHash(w);
            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, w.length());
        }
        stream = new LinkedList<>();
    }

    public boolean query(char c) {
        stream.add(c);
        if(stream.size() > maxLen) {
            stream.remove(0);
        }
        String s = "";
        int hash = 0;
        for(int i = stream.size()-1; i >= 0; --i) {
            s = stream.get(i) + s;
            int v = (int) stream.get(i).charValue()-'a';
            hash = ((hash * 26) + v) % MOD;
            if(!suffixes.contains(hash)) {
                return false;
            } else if(wordMap.containsKey(hash) && wordMap.get(hash).contains(s)) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    private void addRollingHash(String s) {
        int hash = 0;
        for(int i = s.length()-1; i >= 0; --i) {
            int v = s.charAt(i)-'a';
            hash = ((hash * 26) + v) % MOD;
            suffixes.add(hash);
        }
        Set<String> set = wordMap.getOrDefault(hash, new HashSet<String>());
        set.add(s);
        wordMap.put(hash, set);
    }
}
```

