solutions.content:
A dictionary and a list of letters, which easily makes one to come up with a solution of trie. If you are not familiar with trie, it is better to study this data structure now. Because it is asked frequently in an interview these days. 
So, with a trie we can check whether a string is in a dictionary efficiently. But in this question, it tells us to check the last k letters, which means we have to start from the last letter and trace back. To make our work easier, we just construct the trie with a reverse order:
```
["abc", "fc", "ae"]
Normal order trie:  abc, fc, ae
           NA
		  /  \
		 a    f
	    /  \  |
	   b    e c
	   |
	   c
Reversed order trie: cba, cf, ea
           NA
		  /  \
		 c    e
	    /  \  |
	   b    f a
	   |
	   a
```
Whenever we want to check a stream like "abc", we just start with the order "c-b-a" and search the reversed order trie. 
Time complexity: O(nm) to construct the trie and O(h) for each query, where n is the length of the dictionary, m is the length of words in dictionary, and h is the height of trie. 
Space complexity: O(nm + q), where q is the number of characters we maintained in deque. As the max height of trie is h, so we can limit the size of q to be h. 
```java
class StreamChecker {
    Trie trie;
    Deque<Character> cur;
    int cap;
    public StreamChecker(String[] words) {
        trie = new Trie(words);
        cur = new ArrayDeque();
        cap = trie.height;
    }

    public boolean query(char letter) {
        cur.offerLast(letter);
        if(cur.size() > cap) cur.pollFirst();
        return trie.search(new ArrayList(cur));
    }
}

class TrieNode {
    TrieNode[] next;
    boolean term;
    public TrieNode() {
        next = new TrieNode[26];
        term = false;
    }
}

class Trie {
    TrieNode root;
    int height;
    public Trie(String[] words) {
        root = new TrieNode();
        height = 0;
        for(String word: words) {
            TrieNode cur = root;
            height = Math.max(height, word.length());
            for(int i = word.length() - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
                char c = word.charAt(i);
                if(cur.next[c-'a'] == null) cur.next[c-'a'] = new TrieNode();
                cur = cur.next[c-'a'];
            }
            cur.term = true;
        }
    }
    public boolean search(List<Character> s) {
        TrieNode cur = root;
        for(int i = s.size() - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
            char c = s.get(i);
            if(cur.next[c-'a'] == null) return false;
            cur = cur.next[c-'a'];
            if(cur.term) return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```

