solutions.content:
When we get the input of string array, we creat a table(implemented by 2 layer HashMap) to classfify all the words by the last character and the length of the words. 
For example, if we have ["ab", "eb", "abb", "cdb", "cd"], we get:
b:  [2, "ab, eb"], [3, "abb", "cdb"]
d:  [1, "cd"].

We put all the queried letter in a Stringbuilder sb. For a query, let's say 'b', we try the length of 2 and 3, and see the string comstructed by the last 2 or 3 qurried letter is contains in the correspondin set or not.


```
class StreamChecker {
    Map<Character, Map<Integer, Set<String>>> map = new HashMap<>();
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();

    public StreamChecker(String[] words) {
        if (words == null || words.length == 0) return;
        for (String s : words) {
            char c = s.charAt(s.length() - 1);
            int length = s.length();
            Map<Integer, Set<String>> newEntry = map.getOrDefault(c, new HashMap<Integer, Set<String>>());
            Set<String> sameLengthSet = newEntry.getOrDefault(length, new HashSet<>());
            sameLengthSet.add(s);
            newEntry.put(length, sameLengthSet);
            map.put(c, newEntry);
        }
    }

    public boolean query(char letter) {
        sb.append(letter);
        Map<Integer, Set<String>> newEntry = map.get(letter);
        if (newEntry == null) return false;
        for (int length : newEntry.keySet()) {
            if (length > sb.length()) continue;
            Set<String> setWithSameLength = newEntry.get(length);
            String target = sb.substring(sb.length() - length, sb.length());
            if (setWithSameLength.contains(target)) return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}

